bib.title: Approaching neutron-rich nuclei toward the r-process path in peripheral heavy-ion collisions at 15 MeV/nucleon

Experiment performed at the Cyclotron
Institute of Texas AM University using K500
superconducting cyclotron
Compiled by S.H.
Reaction products were analyzed with momentum
achromat recoil separator (MARS). MARS consisted of
QQDQDDQQ sequence of quadrupoles (Q) and dipoles (D).
Magnetic optics formed dispersive image after first
dipole and an achromatic image at the end of MARS.
At the position of dispersive image a parallel
plate avalanche counter was placed to provide
reaction product position and start of time of flight
measurement
At the achromatic focal point a
second parallel plate counter with a silicon dE-E
telescope was placed. PPAC provided stop time signal
for time of flight and position of reaction product.
E-dE telescope provided information for particle
identification
